From: Daniel van Vugt <daniel.van.vugt@canonical.com>
Date: Fri, 6 Mar 2026 15:14:48 +0800
Subject: ply-utils: Always "guess" the device scale

Actually the naming here is misleading because "guessing" makes the
decision more reliable and always determined by the screen resolution.

If "guessing" is disallowed then you get a less predictable algorithm
which will change its answer depending on the physical DPI of the screen.
However, the availability of DPI information will change depending on
when the daemon is started.

During early boot using 'simpledrm', DPI information is not available
so we are always "guessing" and get a predictable result based on
resolution alone. After booting, such as during shutdown, we have full
DRM drivers available and so also now have DPI information. This means
we no longer need to "guess" the best scale and can use the DPI to
decide to change scale 2.0 back to 1.0 if the physical display is large
enough. But this results in a shutdown splash that's a different size
to the boot splash, and also a shutdown splash that's too small in the
case of 4K displays if those displays are also physically large.

This patch is a one-liner to minimize conflicts and make patch maintenance
easy, but it won't be upstreamed in this form. Instead we will be
proposing a larger patch upstream later to remove the non-guessing code
path because it's never actually helpful, causes inconsistency and
adds complexity.

Bug: https://gitlab.freedesktop.org/plymouth/plymouth/-/issues/308
Ubuntu-Bug: https://bugs.launchpad.net/bugs/2116296
Forwarded: no
---
 src/libply/ply-utils.c | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/src/libply/ply-utils.c b/src/libply/ply-utils.c
index 7524b3c..d79fef4 100644
--- a/src/libply/ply-utils.c
+++ b/src/libply/ply-utils.c
@@ -1069,7 +1069,7 @@ get_device_scale (uint32_t width,
         if (overridden_device_scale != 0)
                 return overridden_device_scale;
 
-        if (guess)
+        if (true)
                 return get_device_scale_guess (width, height);
 
         /* Somebody encoded the aspect ratio (16/9 or 16/10)
